ex1:
    good names:

    - randomNumber (tell the purpose)
    - count (tell the work)
    - i (simple and culture)

    bad names:

    - itCreateAPesudoNumberForYouThenToGuessAndWin (too long)
    - 2lazy (number at the start)
    - alf-jd@@@ (illegal symbol)

ex2:
    1. "2" because it is division of 2 integers, therefore the result is an integer
    2. "2.33333" because it's a result of a float type number divide an integer type
    3. same as 2

ex3:
    #include <iostream>
    using namespace std;

    int main(){
        int G1, G2, G3;
        
        cout << "Enter the first game score: ";
        cin >> G1;
        cout << "Enter the second game score: ";
        cin >> G2;
        cout << "Enter the third game score: ";
        cin >> G3;
        cout << "Your average game score is: " << (G1 + G2 + G3)/3;
        
        return 0;
    }